Traveling can be hectic and, at times, stressful. Whether you’re traveling for business or just taking a trip for pleasure, the increase in activity, changes in environment, and differences in cultural expectations can be overwhelming.

One way to bring mindfulness into our lives is to sprinkle it throughout the day to help reduce feelings of stress and anxiety. Here is one tip for incorporating mindfulness into your day:

Practice mindful eating and what better place than Napoli to mindfully eat pizza:
* 	Start by looking at what you are planning to eat. What do you notice visually?
* 	Now, smell the food carefully.  What do you notice?
* 	If applicable, do you notice any sounds?  If you’re eating something like a raisin, try holding it close to your ear as you squeeze it gently. Or if you’re unwrapping a chocolate, listen to the crinkles of the wrapper as you unfold it.
* 	What do you feel with your fingers? Is the food warm or cold? Is it smooth, rough, or sticky?
* 	Now, put the piece of food on your tongue, but don’t chew on it yet. Just leave it on your tongue and notice how it feels in your mouth. Do you taste anything yet? What activity do you notice in your mouth?
* 	Start chewing it, very slowly, just one bite at a time. Notice how the tastes change as you chew.
* 	Try to notice when you swallow, and see how far you can feel the food into your body.

Paris will always be a good idea ♥️ 

Traveling alone can be an exciting and transformative experience, but it can also be daunting, especially if you’re new to solo traveling or like in my case, the plan was never to be alone. I was supposed to meet with my BF who got stranded in the airport because of flight cancellations. 

This was not my first time traveling alone but the difference was that the other occasions I had a goal, the first time was when I went from LA to Texas for our book (Doctoras con Alas) tour and I meet with my friends and co-authors there. The second time I flew to Florida to see my family.

However this time, I didn’t have any plans. In fact, I did have plans but it was all with my friend. So it was very hard for me to learn she wasn’t coming right when my plane was taking off. I couldn’t even get off the plane. I had a lot of anxiety, the slightest turbulence would made me spiral and think the plane was going to crash 🤦🏽‍♀️

When I landed in Lyon I was excited to explore the city and still had the hopes that my friend was going to be able to get on the next flight. That night I didn’t sleep waiting for her to tell me she made it through the waitlist. 

The next day I flew to Paris and again started to have a lot of anxiety because that day French government pass pension reform bill and protest erupt all around the city, watching the news seeing protestors burning cars, piling rubbish bags, barricades were set on fire was very stressful. I had a panic attack. 

The following morning after my yoga session I felt ready and decided to go out and enjoy the rest of my trip. I had an amazing time and I definitely recommend it! And the last night my friend finally arrived, I only got to see her for a few hours but was happy to spend some time with her.

Traveling alone can be a great way to practice self-care and reconnect with yourself by prioritizing the things you love and enjoy, taking time to slow down you can create a transformative experience for yourself. It was like my very own DIY retreat ✨

This spring break, the number one question I got asked is: How do I practice mindfulness with my family while on Vacation? 

Holidays are a great opportunity to spend quality time with your family, but it can also be a hectic and overwhelming experience, especially when traveling with young children. However, practicing mindfulness can help you and your family fully enjoy your time together and create long-lasting memories. Here are some tips on how to practice mindfulness with your children while on vacation and the benefits of doing so.

-Start the day with a mindful activity: Begin your day with a simple mindfulness exercise such as breathing exercises, our favorite is doing yoga or a guided meditation. This will help you and your children start the day in a calm and focused state of mind, making it easier to navigate any unexpected events that may arise.

-Encourage mindful observation: Encourage your children to notice their surroundings and take in the details of their environment. You can do this by playing games such as "I Spy" or our favorite, taking a nature walk where you ask them to point out interesting objects and sights.

-Practice gratitude: Take some time to express gratitude for the things you have, the people you love, and the experiences you are having. You can do this by asking each family member to share something they are grateful for each day. We do this every night before bedtime.

-Set aside technology: Vacations are a great time to unplug and disconnect from technology. Set aside specific times of the day to check your phone or use your devices, and spend the rest of your time engaging with each other and the world around you.

-Encourage mindful eating: Help your children to be present during mealtimes by encouraging them to eat slowly and savor each bite. Talk about the flavors and textures of the food, and enjoy the experience of eating together as a family.

By making mindfulness a part of your vacation routine, you can help your family create meaningful memories and strengthen your bond with each other ✨

✈️ Mindful Travel Tip: Helping Kids with Meltdowns 🌟

As parents and caregivers, we all know that traveling with kids can be both exciting and challenging. Meltdowns can happen unexpectedly, causing stress and anxiety for everyone involved. Today, I'd like to share a powerful tool that can make a world of difference during your family adventures: mindfulness!

💡 How can mindfulness assist during meltdowns? 💡

1️⃣ Stay Calm: As a parent, practice mindfulness first. When you're calm and centered, it becomes easier to guide your child through their emotions.

2️⃣ Tune in to Your Child: When you notice signs of frustration or anxiety in your child, take a moment to connect with them. Validate their feelings and let them know it's okay to feel this way.

3️⃣ Breathing Exercises: Encourage deep breathing exercises for both you and your child. Taking slow, deep breaths can help relax the nervous system and ease tension.

4️⃣ A Mindfulness Scavenger Hunt is an exciting way to keep kids grounded and connected with their surroundings during travel. It encourages them to explore their environment in a mindful and present way, engaging their senses and cultivating a sense of wonder.

Grounding exercises like this empower children to manage their emotions, fostering emotional resilience and a deeper connection with the world around them. Moreover, it creates beautiful memories of shared mindfulness experiences that will last a lifetime.

✨Here are three quick & easy techniques to calm stress and anxiety: 

1. Be mindful with a cup of tea (or your favorite drink) 🍵Transform a simple act into a moment of mindfulness by savoring your favorite drink. Start by observing the cup in your hands. Feel its warmth, its texture. Take a moment to inhale the aroma, allowing it to awaken your senses. As you take that first sip, pay attention to the taste, the temperature, and the way it soothes you from the inside out. Allow this act to become a ritual of self-care. Let each sip be a reminder that you deserve this moment of tranquility.

2. Double inhale breathing 
Deep breathing is a quiet powerhouse when it comes to stress relief. It activates your body’s relaxation response, bringing instant calm. 
* Inhale long, through your nose, until almost full 
* Inhale again quickly, until full 
* Take a slow exhale through your mouth. 

3. Doodling 
Let your creativity flow as you mindfully doodle. Allow your thoughts to flow onto the page, forming shapes, patterns, or whatever emerges naturally. This simple act engages your senses and provides a gentle escape from the pressures of the day. It’s a reminder that even in the busiest moments, you have the ability to find calm within yourself. Let go of any judgment or expectation. 
✍🏼Combining doodling with affirmations creates a holistic approach to stress relief. By consistently repeating these statements, we can rewire our thought patterns and cultivate a more optimistic outlook.

Remember, mindfulness is about being fully present, and even the most ordinary activities can become a source of inner peace when approached with intention and awareness.

It was a pleasure to have a visit from Dr Sandy Zanella yesterday at the Dojo for The Warrior Academy Podcast! 
We tackle the controversial topic of medicating kids as a first line of treatment and put private health care in the spot light here as we ask some uncomfortable questions. 

Why are Dr’s rewarded for selling medicine over treating patients? 

Why are Dr’s encouraged to reach a minimum quota for drugs sold? 

Why do we live in a society that gives children medicine as a first line of treatment? 

Why is there this disconnect between the mind and the body in the west? 

What is the solution for parents and what should we be aware of? 

Why is mindfulness one of the key components to raising resilient kids? 

What is mindful parenting and how can we really support our children to be more present? 

I think the majority of mental health challenges we face with young people stem from the topics we have spoken about in this interview. It’s a massive eye opener. Sandy has such a depth of knowledge coming from her professional background as a physician to building a business that supports parents, children and schools in cultivating self compassion and mindful practices. Incredibly aligned with our work here at The Warrior Academy!

Thank you Sandy for your time and insights!

Consider incorporating mindfulness practices during visits to nature places, whether it’s a serene beach, a tranquil park, or @thegreenplanetdubai . Here’s a guide to cultivating mindfulness amidst the holiday chaos:

✨Pre-Trip Mindful Preparation: Before going, take a few moments to set mindful intentions. Reflect on the purpose of the visit, whether it’s to find tranquility, connect with family, or simply appreciate the beauty of nature.

🫁 Mindful Breathing Exercises: Begin the sanctuary visit with mindful breathing exercises. Take slow, deep breaths, inhaling positivity and exhaling any tension. This practice establishes a mindful foundation for the experience.

🌿 Mindful walking: Be aware of each step, the textures beneath your feet, and the sensations of movement. This mindful approach transforms the visit into a walking meditation.

🙏🏽 Gratitude: Take a moment to express gratitude for the beauty and diversity of the animal kingdom. This mindful acknowledgment deepens the connection with nature and fosters a sense of appreciation.

💭 Reflective time: Allow yourself to absorb the experiences mindfully, acknowledging the emotions and thoughts that arise.

🐛 Observing Animal Behaviors Mindfully:
While observing animals, engage in mindful observation. Pay attention to their movements, behaviors, and interactions. Practice being fully present in the moment, allowing the sights and sounds of the wildlife to anchor you in the now.
